Title:
Abusing a Lenovo “BootRepair” Driver IOCTL to Terminate Arbitrary Processes (PhantomKiller for dummies)

Type:
Blog Post

Short Summary (4–8 sentences max):
- This post walks through reversing a signed Lenovo kernel driver to find an exposed IOCTL that enables terminating arbitrary processes from user mode.  
- The author identifies the vulnerable code path by hunting for sensitive ntoskrnl imports (notably `ZwTerminateProcess`) and tracing cross-references in IDA to the `IRP_MJ_DEVICE_CONTROL` handler.  
- The driver’s IOCTL handler takes a 4-byte PID, uses `PsLookupProcessByProcessId` to get an `EPROCESS`, converts it to a process handle via `ObOpenObjectByPointer`, then calls `ZwTerminateProcess`, effectively bypassing normal user-mode access checks.  
- The write-up shows how to recover the device name/symbolic link (`\\.\BootRepair`), the IOCTL code, and the required input buffer size, then build a minimal C/C++ console app using `CreateFile` + `DeviceIoControl`.  
- It demonstrates a BYOVD-style primitive useful for killing protected/high-integrity processes (e.g., security tools) without needing Test Mode or an unsigned driver.  
- Useful for red teamers/pentesters and defenders analyzing driver attack surface and IOCTL abuse patterns.

Technical Focus:
- Windows driver IOCTL reversing (IDA, xrefs, `IRP_MJ_DEVICE_CONTROL`)
- BYOVD (Bring Your Own Vulnerable Driver) process-kill primitive
- Kernel APIs: `ZwTerminateProcess`, `PsLookupProcessByProcessId`, `ObOpenObjectByPointer`
- Device object namespaces and symbolic links (`\DosDevices\`, `\\.\` paths)
- User-mode exploitation via `CreateFile` / `DeviceIoControl`

Use Cases:
- Terminate EDR/AV or other high-integrity processes using a signed vulnerable driver
- Validate and reproduce a driver IOCTL vulnerability during research
- Build detections around suspicious IOCTL usage and known-abusable device names
- Driver attack-surface auditing by scanning for dangerous kernel imports and weak IOCTL validation

Keywords:
BYOVD, Lenovo driver, BootRepair, PhantomKiller, IOCTL, IRP_MJ_DEVICE_CONTROL, DeviceIoControl, CreateFile, \DosDevices, symbolic link, ZwTerminateProcess, PsLookupProcessByProcessId, ObOpenObjectByPointer, EPROCESS, process termination, kernel driver exploitation, DriverEntry, ntoskrnl imports, Driver Signature Enforcement (DSE)